evival\n|-\n|1980\n|\n|\n|[[Tony Award|Tony Award's Lawrence Langner Memorial Award]]\n|}\n\n==Filmography and Awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Film\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n|1910\n|''[[Jean and the Calico Doll]]'' and one subsequent [[Vitagraph Studios|Vitagraph]] film\n| Juvenile lead\n| Hayes recalled in a 1931 interview with ''The New York Times'' that she had played the juvenile lead in two films starring [[Jean (dog)|Jean]], the Vitagraph dog.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Murphy |first1=Donn B. |last2=Moore |first2=Stephen |date=1993 |title=Helen Hayes: A Bio-Bibliography |url=https://archive.org/details/helenhayesbiobib0000murp/page/153 |location=Westport, Connecticut |publisher=Greenwood Press |page=[https://archive.org/details/helenhayesbiobib0000murp/page/153 153] |isbn=9780313277931 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=March 15, 1931 |title=Miss Hayes and Films |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9D04E3DB1F30E633A25756C1A9659C946094D6CF |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |location= |access-date=2015-11-28 |quote=I'm afraid my former career in the movies doesn't mean much, but when I was 8 years old and had just made my first stage appearance, in a Lew Fields musical show, 'Old Dutch', my mother took me over to the old Vitagraph studio in Brooklyn. I had long curls and they let me play the juvenile lead in two pictures in support of Jean, the collie. Jean was the most famous dog of the day and I was very thrilled.}}</ref>\n|-\n|1917\n|''The Weavers of Life''\n|Peggy\n|\n|-\n|1928\n|''[[The Dancing Town]]''\n|Olive Pepperall\n|Short subject\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1931\n|''[[The Sin of Madelon Claudet]]''\n|Madelon Claudet\n|[[Academy Award for Best Actress]]\n|-\n|''[[Arrowsmith (film)|Arrowsmith]]''\n|Leora Arrowsmith\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1932\n|''[[A Farewell to Arms (1932 film)|