a\n|''Four Women in Black''\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1958\n|''Omnibus''\n|Mrs. Howard V. Larue III\n|''Mrs. McThing''\n|-\n|''[[The United States Steel Hour]]''\n|Mother Seraphim\n|''One Red Rose for Christmas''<br />Nominated\u2014[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress \u2013 Miniseries or a Movie|Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress \u2013 Miniseries or a Movie]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1959\n|''[[Hallmark Hall of Fame]]''\n|Essie\n|''[[Ah, Wilderness!]]''\n|-\n|''[[Play of the Week]]''\n|Madame Ranevskaya\n|''[[The Cherry Orchard]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=3|1960\n|''[[The Bell Telephone Hour]]''\n|Baroness Nadedja von Meck\n|''The Music of Romance''\n|-\n|''[[Play of the Week]]''\n|Mother Hildebrand\n|''The Velvet Glove''\n|-\n|''[[Dow Hour of Great Mysteries]]''\n|Letitia Van Gorder\n|''[[The Bat (play)|The Bat]]'' by [[Mary Roberts Rinehart]]\n|-\n|1961\n|''[[Michael Shayne]]''\n|\n|''Murder Round My Wrist''\n|-\n|1963\n|''[[The Christophers]]''\n|\n|''What One Bootmaker Did''\n|-\n|1967\n|''[[Tarzan (1966 TV series)|Tarzan]]''\n|Mrs. Wilson\n|''The Pride of the Lioness''\n|-\n|1969\n|''Arsenic and Old Lace''\n|Abby Brewster\n|\n|-\n|1970\n|''The Front Page''\n|Narrator\n|\n|-\n|1971\n|''[[Do Not Fold, Spindle or Mutilate]]''\n|Sophie Tate Curtis\n|Nominated\u2014[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress \u2013 Miniseries or a Movie|Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress \u2013 Miniseries or a Movie]]\n|-\n|rowspan=3|1972\n|''[[Harvey (film)#Remakes|Harvey]]''\n|Veta Louise Simmons\n|\n|-\n|''[[Here's Lucy]]''\n|Mrs. Kathleen Brady\n|''Lucy and the Little Old Lady''\n|-\n|''[[Ghost Story (TV series)|Ghost Story]]''\n|Miss Gilden\n|''Alter-Ego''\n|-\n|1973\u20131974\n|''[[The Snoop Sisters]]''\n|Ernesta Snoop\n|Nominated\u2014[[Emmy Award|Emmy Award for Best Lead Actress in a Limited Series]]\n|-\n|1975\n|''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]''\n|Aunt Clara\n|''Retire in Sunny Hawaii... Forever''<br />Nominated\u2014[[Emmy Award|Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress for a Single Appearance in a Drama or Comedy Series]]<br />Co-starred with her son [[James MacArthur]] (who played her nephew in the episode).\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1976\n|''[[The Moneychangers]]''\n|Dr. McCartney\n|miniseries\n|-\n|''[[Victory at Entebbe]]''\n|Etta Grossman-Wise\n|\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[A Family Upside Down]]''\n|Emma Long\n|Nominated\u2014[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress \u2013 Miniseries or a Movie|Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress \u2013 Miniseries or a Movie]]\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[The Love Boat]]''\n|Agatha Winslow\n|''No Girls for Doc/Marriage of Convenience/The Caller/The Witness''\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1982\n|''[[Love, Sidney]]''\n|Mrs. Clovis\n|''Pro and Cons''\n|-\n|''[[Murder Is Easy]]''\n|Lavinia Fullerton\n|\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[A Caribbean Mystery (film)|A Caribbean Mystery]]''\n|[[Miss Marple]]\n|\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Highway to Heaven]]''\n|Estelle Wicks\n|\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Murder with Mirrors]]''\n|[[Miss Marple]]\n|Final TV role\n|}\n\n===Other awards===\nIn 1973, Hayes was inducted into the [[National Women's Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womenofthehall.org/inductee/helen-hayes/|title=Hayes, Helen|website=National Women\u2019s Hall of Fame}}</ref> In 1979, the [[Supersisters]] trading card set was produced and distributed; one of the cards featured Hayes's name and picture.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wulf |first=Steve |url=http://espn.go.com/espnw/news-commentary/article/12535055/original-roster |title=Supersisters: Original Roster |publisher=Espn.go.com |date=2015-03-23 |accessdate=2015-06-04}}</ref> In 1983, Hayes received the Award for Greatest Public Service Benefiting the Disadvantaged, an award given out annually by [[Jefferson Awards for Public Service|Jefferson Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeffersonawards.org/pastwinners/national|title=Jefferson Awards FoundationNational \u2013 Jefferson Awards Foundation|work=Jefferson Awards Foundation|accessdate=22 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101124043935/http://jeffersonawards.org/pastwinners/national|archive-date=24 November 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of persons who have won Academy, Emmy, Grammy, and Tony Awards]]\n* [[List of actors with Academy Award nominations]]\n*[[List of people from Morelos, Mexico]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*Mosel, Tad and Macy, Gertrude. ''Leading Lady:  The World and Theatre of Katharine Cornell''(1978), Little, Brown & Co, Boston, {{ISBN|0-316-58537-8}}\n*Murphy, Donn B. and Moore, Stephen. ''Helen Hayes; A Bio-Bibliography'' (1993)\n*Kennedy, Harold J. ''No Pickle, No Performance. An Irreverent Theatrical Excursion from Tallulah to Travolta'', Doubleday & Co. (1978)\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{commons}}\n* {{IMDb name|371040}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|8149}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070304010247/http://www.helenhayes.com/ Official site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050828191044/http://www.stevemoore.addr.com/hayes.html Tribute site]\n* [http://www.nypl.org/archives/4402 Helen Hayes papers, 1817\u20131963 (bulk dates 1905\u20131963)], held by the Billy Rose Theatre Division, [[New York Public Library for the Performing Arts]]\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wnet/americanmasters/database/hayes_h.html American Masters] (PBS)\n* [http://www.helenhayes.org/ The Helen Hayes Awards]\n* [http://film.virtual-history.com/person.php?personid=1042 Photographs of Helen Hayes]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110721054307/http://www.nea.gov/honors/medals/medalists_year.html#88#88 Lifetime Honors \u2013 National Medal of Arts]\n*[http://www.HelenHayesHospital.org Helen Hayes Hospital] \n*[http://hhhfoundation.net Helen Hayes Hospital Foundation]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Helen Hayes\n|list =\n{{AcademyAwardBestActress 1927-1940}}\n{{AcademyAwardBestSupportingActress 1961-1980}}\n{{Distinguished Performance Award}}\n{{EmmyAward DramaLeadActress}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Spoken Word Album 1970s}}\n{{Kennedy Center Honorees 1980s}}\n{{National Medal of Arts recipients 1980s|state=autocollapse}} \n{{National Women's Hall of Fame}}\n{{Special Tony Award}}\n{{TonyAward PlayLeadActress 1947-1975}}\n{{Volpi Cup for Best Actress}}\n}}\n{{EGOT winners}}\n{{Triple Crown of Acting winners}}\n{{Charles MacArthur}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hayes, Helen}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Best Actress Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actress Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Lead Actress in a Drama Series Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Kennedy Center honorees]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Actresses of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:United States National Medal of Arts recipients]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:Volpi Cup for Best Actress winners]]\n[[Category:Volpi Cup winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Laetare Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:People from Cuernavaca]]\n[[Category:People from Morelos]]\n[[Category:People from Nyack, New York]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision Appearances and Awards", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helen_Hayes"}
{"title_page": "Jean Fernand", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name         = Jean Fernand\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| alt          =\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1948|11|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Orly]], France\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| resting_place= \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality  = French\n| field        = Painting, drawing, [[sculpture]], [[printmaking]]\n| training     = \n| movement     = [[Impressionism]]<br />[[Modernism]]<br />\n| works        = \n| patrons      = \n| awards       =\n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n}}\n\n'''Jean Fernand''' (born 19 November 1948) is a French [[impressionist]] painter, lithographer, sculptor and illustrator.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jean Fernand biography|url= https://www.frenchartcollection.com/gb/impressionism/923-french-landscape-jean-fernand-drawing.html |date=2020-02-04|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en}}</ref> He is known for its paintings and drawings with characters and Venetian atmospheres. \n\n==History==\n\nJean Fernand was born in 1948 in [[Orly]], {{convert|30|km}} south of [[Paris]]. His parents, who were Parisians, managed an industrial laundry. When he left the primary school, Jean Fernand passed his launderer certificate; he was therefore destined to take up the family business. His grandfather was a painter who also lacquered [[Napoleon]]'s tomb, so Fernand was already very interested in painting and drawing since childhood.\n\nAt the age of 16, he began to paint. He received painting classes from several artists such as Andr\u00e9 Bergeron and Gozlan. From the age of 25, he gradually devoted himself to painting, gradually forming his style. In 1970, he opened an art studio in Orly.<ref>{{cite web|title=29art \u2013 artist gallery|url= http://29art.com/e/index.php?document_srl=15960&dummy=1|date=2020-02-04|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en}}</ref> \n\nHis first exhibition took place in 1970 in the [[Salon des Ind\u00e9pendants]] in Paris. His works have been exhibited in Switzerland, Japan, Sweden, Norway, Germany, Belgium, Japan and the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jean Fernand biography|url= https://www.marcel-spilliaert.com/jean-fernand-1948--2066|date=2020-02-04|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en}}</ref> \nDuring the seventies, he illustrated also some stories by [[Edgar Allan Poe]] for the publishing house Cercle Europ\u00e9en du Livre. He became friends with the painter Francis Goubault, originally from [[Choisy-le-Roi]]. Together, they created different frescoes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Francis Goubault biography|url= http://francis-goubault.com/|date=2020-02-04|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en}}</ref> \n\nHe won several art prizes, including the first prize at [[L\u00e9zignan-Corbi\u00e8res]] in 2003.\n\n==Selected works==\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Marcel Spillaert - Jean Fernand Biography|url= https://www.marcel-spilliaert.com/jean-fernand-1948--2066|date=2020-02-04|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en}}</ref>\n\n* ''Banquet'' (60 x 30 cm)\n* ''Foule'' (103 cm x 17 cm)\n* ''Traversee du desert'' (93 cm x 46 cm)\n* ''Concerto'' (41 x 53 cm)\n* ''Conciliabule'' (43 x 43 cm)\n* ''La Gente Dame'' (painting, 22 x 16 cm)\n* ''Bouquet de Roses'' (65 x 81 cm)\n* ''Couple'' (painting, 74 x 65 cm)<ref>{{cite web|title=Hotel du Parc, Art moderne & Contemporain |url= http://encheres-alsace.fr/files/963_Catalogue%20VP%20Mulhouse%2023%20septembre%202012.pdf |date=2020-02-04|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en}}</ref> \n* ''Le Lever'' (47 x 33 cm)\n* ''Cavali\u00e8re'' (drawing, 23 x 18 cm)\n* ''Au Coeur de la Bataille'' (painting, 28 x 60 cm)\n* ''Troubadour'' (54 x 92 cm)\n* ''Vue au Loin'' (56 x 24 cm)\n* ''Course au Pre'' (80 x 37 cm)\n* ''Notre Dame de Paris'' (60 x 26 cm)\n\n==Selected exhibitions==\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Jean Fernand \u2013 Official curriculum vitae|url= http://fernand.jean.free.fr/act/cv-francais.pdf |date=2020-02-04|access-date=2020-02-04|language=fr}}</ref> \n\n=== French art salons ===\n\n* [[Salon des Ind\u00e9pendants]], [[Grand Palais]], Paris,  (1970\u20131975);\n* Art au Pluriel, [[Ablon]] (1983\u20131984);\n* Le Roi, [[Choisy-le-Roi]] (1985\u20131990);\n* Sculptures en l\u2019\u00eele, [[Andr\u00e9sy]] (2005\u20132006);\n* Salle d'Exposition Francval, [[Arpajon]] (2002\u20132005);\n* Les Artistes du Hurepoix, [[Sainte-Genevi\u00e8ve-des-Bois, Essonne]] (2003\u20132006)\n* Salon Espace des Blancs Manteaux, Paris Cour Circuit (2006)\n* March\u00e9 de l'Art de [[Montparnasse]], Paris (2000\u20132008)\n* La Nuit des Soudeurs, [[Granville, Manche]] (2007)\n* Grand March\u00e9 d'Art Contemporain, [[Bastille]] Paris (2003\u20132008)\n* Trot'art, [[Lognes]] (2004)\n* Thirache Fermi\u00e8re, [[Vervins]] (2004, 2006, 2008, 2010)\n* Brocant'art, [[Conie-Molitard]] (2010, 2012)\n* [[Authon-du-Perche]] (2012)\n* Courant d'Art, [[La Bazoche-Gouet]] (2012)\n* [[Moigny-sur-\u00c9cole]] (2012, 2013)\n* R\u00e9cup'art, [[Roubaix]] (2004\u20132013)\n* Courant d'Art, [[Nogent-le-Rotrou]] (2013)\n\n===Exhibitions in Japan ===\n\nBetween 2008 and 2014, Jean Fernand did several [[traveling exhibition]]s in Japan, where he still actually lives.\n\n* [[Mitsukoshi]] department store in [[Hiroshima]] and [[Nagoya]]\n* Art Gallery, [[Yamagata, Yamagata]]\n* [[Isetan]] department store in [[Tokyo]]\n* [[Daimaru]] department store in [[Fukuoka]]\n\n== Galeries ==\n\n* [[Galerie Ror Volmar]], Paris, France (1970\u20131973);\n* Galerie Ror Volmar, [[Vichy]], France (1971\u20131973);\n* [[Orly Airport]], Orly, France (1972);\n* Catya Graneuf, Paris, France (1974);\n* Galerie du Comte de Vallombreuse, Biarritz, France (1974\u20131975);\n* Belle Epine, [[Basel]], Switzerland\n* Galerie Lambert Monet, [[Geneva]], Switzerland (1976);\n* Galerie Place du march\u00e9, [[Nogent-le-Rotrou]], France (1980);\n* Le Jardin des Arts, [[Ris-Orangis]] (1984\u20132014);\n* Galerie d'art, [[Moret-sur-Loing]], France (1985, 1986, 1987);\n* Galerie de Belle \u00e9pine P. L'Horset, [[Thiais]], France (1975\u20131989);\n* Galerie Audibert, [[Paray-Vieille-Poste ]], France (1980\u20132014),\n* Galerie d'art et d'encadrement, [[Vincennes]], France (1987\u20131990);\n* Les Artistes, [[Choisy-le-Roi]] (1988\u20131990);\n* Fontaine des arts, [[Herblay-sur-Seine]], France (1988\u20131991)\n* Le Jardin des Arts, [[Honfleur]], France (1988\u20132007);\n* Le Jardin des Arts, Paris (1990\u20132007)\n* Galerie de Rambouillet, [[Rambouillet]], France (1999\u20132003)\n* Galerie du Bac, La Varenne-Saint-Hilaire,  [[Saint-Maur-des-Foss\u00e9s]], France (1999\u20132012)\n* Galerie de la Norville, [[La Norville]], France (2001) \n* Galerie Bodou, [[Vincennes]] (2002\u20132013)\n* Galerie des arts, [[Cholet]], France (2002\u20132008)\n* L\u2019encadreur Christian Fiercin, [[Dijon]], France (2003\u20132009)\n* Galerie Rapha\u00ebl, [[Versailles]], France (2003\u20132010)\n* La Fontaine des Arts, [[Herblay]], France (2004\u20132005)\n* L'art et Encadrement, [[Rambouillet]], France (2004\u20132006)\n* Galerie Saint Honorer, [[Versailles]], France (2004\u20132009) \n* L\u2019ile Saint Louis, Paris, France (2005)\n* Galerie Les R\u00e9-cr\u00e9ateurs, Paris, France (2006)\n* Galerie Champalou, [[Limoges]], France (2007\u20132011)\n* Galerie Maciano, Paris, France (2008)\n* Bateau Lavoir, Honfleur, France (2008\u20132012) \n* Barbizon, Seine-et-Marne, (2012\u20132014)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://fernand.jean.free.fr/biographie.htm Official site]\n\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century French painters]]\n[[Category:French male painters]]\n[[Category:French painters]]\n[[Category:French landscape painters]]\n[[Category:French Impressionist painters]]\n[[Category:Modern painters]]\n[[Category:Abstract painters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name         = Jean Fernand\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| alt          =\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1948|11|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Orly]], France\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| resting_place= \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality  = French\n| field        = Painting, drawing, [[sculpture]], [[printmaking]]\n| training     = \n| movement     = [[Impressionism]]<br />[[Modernism]]<br />\n| works        = \n| patrons      = \n| awards       =\n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n}}\n\n'''Jean Fernand''' (born 19 November 1948) is a French [[impressionist]] painter, lithographer, sculptor and illustrator.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jean Fernand biography|url= https://www.frenchartcollection.com/gb/impressionism/923-french-landscape-jean-fernand-drawing.html |date=2020-02-04|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en}}</ref> He is known for its paintings and drawings with characters and Venetian atmospheres. \n\n==History==\n\nJean Fernand was born in 1948 in [[Orly]], {{convert|30|km}} south of [[Paris]]. His parents, who were Parisians, managed an industrial laundry. When he left the primary school, Jean Fernand passed his launderer certificate; he was therefore destined to take up the family business. His grandfather was a painter who also lacquered [[Napoleon]]'s tomb, so Fernand was already very interested in painting and drawing since childhood.\n\nAt the age of 16, he began to paint. He received painting classes from several artists such as Andr\u00e9 Bergeron and Gozlan. From the age of 25, he gradually devoted himself to painting, gradually forming his style. In 1970, he opened an art studio in Orly.<ref>{{cite web|title=29art \u2013 artist gallery|url= http://29art.com/e/index.php?document_srl=15960&dummy=1|date=2020-02-04|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en}}</ref> \n\nHis first exhibition took place in 1970 in the [[Salon des Ind\u00e9pendants]] in Paris. His works have been exhibited in Switzerland, Japan, Sweden, Norway, Germany, Belgium, Japan and the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jean Fernand biography|url= https://www.marcel-spilliaert.com/jean-fernand-1948--2066|date=2020-02-04|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en}}</ref> \nDuring the seventies, he illustrated also some stories by [[Edgar Allen Poe]] for the publishing house Cercle Europ\u00e9en du Livre. He became friends with the painter Francis Goubault, originally from [[Choisy-le-Roi]]. Together, they created different frescoes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Francis Goubault biography|url= http://francis-goubault.com/|date=2020-02-04|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en}}</ref> \n\nHe won several art prizes, including the first prize at [[L\u00e9zignan-Corbi\u00e8res]] in 2003.\n\n==Selected works==\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Marcel Spillaert - Jean Fernand Biography|url= https://www.marcel-spilliaert.com/jean-fernand-1948--2066|date=2020-02-04|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en}}</ref>\n\n* ''Banquet'' (60 x 30 cm)\n* ''Foule'' (103 cm x 17 cm)\n* ''Traversee du desert'' (93 cm x 46 cm)\n* ''Concerto'' (41 x 53 cm)\n* ''Conciliabule'' (43 x 43 cm)\n* ''La Gente Dame'' (painting, 22 x 16 cm)\n* ''Bouquet de Roses'' (65 x 81 cm)\n* ''Couple'' (painting, 74 x 65 cm)<ref>{{cite web|title=Hotel du Parc, Art moderne & Contemporain |url= http://encheres-alsace.fr/files/963_Catalogue%20VP%20Mulhouse%2023%20septembre%202012.pdf |date=2020-02-04|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en}}</ref> \n* ''Le Lever'' (47 x 33 cm)\n* ''Cavali\u00e8re'' (drawing, 23 x 18 cm)\n* ''Au Coeur de la Bataille'' (painting, 28 x 60 cm)\n* ''Troubadour'' (54 x 92 cm)\n* ''Vue au Loin'' (56 x 24 cm)\n* ''Course au Pre'' (80 x 37 cm)\n* ''Notre Dame de Paris'' (60 x 26 cm)\n\n==Selected exhibitions==\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Jean Fernand \u2013 Official curriculum vitae|url= http://fernand.jean.free.fr/act/cv-francais.pdf |date=2020-02-04|access-date=2020-02-04|language=fr}}</ref> \n\n=== French art salons ===\n\n* [[Salon des Ind\u00e9pendants]], [[Grand Palais]], Paris,  (1970\u20131975);\n* Art au Pluriel, [[Ablon]] (1983\u20131984);\n* Le Roi, [[Choisy-le-Roi]] (1985\u20131990);\n* Sculptures en l\u2019\u00eele, [[Andr\u00e9sy]] (2005\u20132006);\n* Salle d'Exposition Francval, [[Arpajon]] (2002\u20132005);\n* Les Artistes du Hurepoix, [[Sainte-Genevi\u00e8ve-des-Bois, Essonne]] (2003\u20132006)\n* Salon Espace des Blancs Manteaux, Paris Cour Circuit (2006)\n* March\u00e9 de l'Art de [[Montparnasse]], Paris (2000\u20132008)\n* La Nuit des Soudeurs, [[Granville, Manche]] (2007)\n* Grand March\u00e9 d'Art Contemporain, [[Bastille]] Paris (2003\u20132008)\n* Trot'art, [[Lognes]] (2004)\n* Thirache Fermi\u00e8re, [[Vervins]] (2004, 2006, 2008, 2010)\n* Brocant'art, [[Conie-Molitard]] (2010, 2012)\n* [[Authon-du-Perche]] (2012)\n* Courant d'Art, [[La Bazoche-Gouet]] (2012)\n* [[Moigny-sur-\u00c9cole]] (2012, 2013)\n* R\u00e9cup'art, [[Roubaix]] (2004\u20132013)\n* Courant d'Art, [[Nogent-le-Rotrou]] (2013)\n\n===Exhibitions in Japan ===\n\nBetween 2008 and 2014, Jean Fernand did several [[traveling exhibition]]s in Japan, where he still actually lives.\n\n* [[Mitsukoshi]] department store in [[Hiroshima]] and [[Nagoya]]\n* Art Gallery, [[Yamagata, Yamagata]]\n* [[Isetan]] department store in [[Tokyo]]\n* [[Daimaru]] department store in [[Fukuoka]]\n\n== Galeries ==\n\n* [[Galerie Ror Volmar]], Paris, France (1970\u20131973);\n* Galerie Ror Volmar, [[Vichy]], France (1971\u20131973);\n* [[Orly Airport]], Orly, France (1972);\n* Catya Graneuf, Paris, France (1974);\n* Galerie du Comte de Vallombreuse, Biarritz, France (1974\u20131975);\n* Belle Epine, [[Basel]], Switzerland\n* Galerie Lambert Monet, [[Geneva]], Switzerland (1976);\n* Galerie Place du march\u00e9, [[Nogent-le-Rotrou]], France (1980);\n* Le Jardin des Arts, [[Ris-Orangis]] (1984\u20132014);\n* Galerie d'art, [[Moret-sur-Loing]], France (1985, 1986, 1987);\n* Galerie de Belle \u00e9pine P. L'Horset, [[Thiais]], France (1975\u20131989);\n* Galerie Audibert, [[Paray-Vieille-Poste ]], France (1980\u20132014),\n* Galerie d'art et d'encadrement, [[Vincennes]], France (1987\u20131990);\n* Les Artistes, [[Choisy-le-Roi]] (1988\u20131990);\n* Fontaine des arts, [[Herblay-sur-Seine]], France (1988\u20131991)\n* Le Jardin des Arts, [[Honfleur]], France (1988\u20132007);\n* Le Jardin des Arts, Paris (1990\u20132007)\n* Galerie de Rambouillet, [[Rambouillet]], France (1999\u20132003)\n* Galerie du Bac, La Varenne-Saint-Hilaire,  [[Saint-Maur-des-Foss\u00e9s]], France (1999\u20132012)\n* Galerie de la Norville, [[La Norville]], France (2001) \n* Galerie Bodou, [[Vincennes]] (2002\u20132013)\n* Galerie des arts, [[Cholet]], France (2002\u20132008)\n* L\u2019encadreur Christian Fiercin, [[Dijon]], France (2003\u20132009)\n* Galerie Rapha\u00ebl, [[Versailles]], France (2003\u20132010)\n* La Fontaine des Arts, [[Herblay]], France (2004\u20132005)\n* L'art et Encadrement, [[Rambouillet]], France (2004\u20132006)\n* Galerie Saint Honorer, [[Versailles]], France (2004\u20132009) \n* L\u2019ile Saint Louis, Paris, France (2005)\n* Galerie Les R\u00e9-cr\u00e9ateurs, Paris, France (2006)\n* Galerie Champalou, [[Limoges]], France (2007\u20132011)\n* Galerie Maciano, Paris, France (2008)\n* Bateau Lavoir, Honfleur, France (2008\u20132012) \n* Barbizon, Seine-et-Marne, (2012\u20132014)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://fernand.jean.free.fr/biographie.htm Official site]\n\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century French painters]]\n[[Category:French male painters]]\n[[Category:French painters]]\n[[Category:French landscape painters]]\n[[Category:French Impressionist painters]]\n[[Category:Modern painters]]\n[[Category:Abstract painters]]\n", "name_user": "Mandarax", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_Fernand"}
